Motivation

July 28

Frustrated by PPO, namely, why does it work, the sensitivity to hyperparameters, trust region value being 0.2 no matter what, and all the implementation details, we set out to figure out if it's possible to make this algorithm simpler. We were inspired by The 37 Implementation Details of PPO, and wanted a more principled way of thinking about tricks and hyperparameters.

Setup

July 28

After looking through the 37 tricks, we devised our own list, with some high-level groupings of the tricks that made sense to us. This resulted in a list of 12 tricks (in 5 categories):

  • Normalization and clipping
    • Normalization of the advantage estimates (remove? or change to symlog) [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Mahvash]
    • Surrogate objective clipping (remove?) [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Paulius]
    • Value function clipping (remove?) [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Mikel]
    • Gradient clipping (remove?) [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Mahvash]
  • Advantage Estimation
    • Change GAE to just advantage prediction [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Fahd]
  • Training setup
    • Use full batch instead of mini-batch [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Kunal]
  • Architecture
    • Check other weight initializations [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Paulius]
    • Change the optimizer from Adam to Muon (or others) [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Mikel]
    • Adam LR scheduler (remove?) [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Mahvash]
    • Use multiple heads (same backbone network) [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Seth]
  • Mujuco-specific
    • Observation clipping (remove?) [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Kunal]
    • Reward scaling (replace with symlog) [ðŸ®²ðŸ®³ Kunal]
We decided to use the PPO implementation from the CleanRL GitHub repository, because it contains all the 37 tricks from the blog post. We chose the HalfCheetah-v4 environment for preliminary runs, with (mostly) 10 experiment replications (seeds). In the plots we show the mean across the 10 runs, and the shaded plot shows the minimum/maximum for a particular timestep.

Baseline

July 29

We ran the baseline with the default hyperparameters from the CleanRL codebase: This set the bar we'd have to meet for our other experiments.

Individual Ablations

July 29

We decided that we need to try out all of tricks removed, one by one. We call this first-order ablations. The results can be seen here:

Some of our conclusions:

  • Muon is doing well.
  • Removing gradient clipping is doing well.
  • Changing reward clipping to symlog is doing well.
  • Removing gradient normalization seems to be doing well.

Group Ablations

July 30

We decided to try changing multiple things in a run, to see how they interact. The different combos we tried are:

  1. Combo 1
    • Muon optimizer
    • Smaller learning rate (0.0003)
    • Remove clipping
  2. Combo 2
    • Muon optimizer
    • Fullbatch
    • No learning rate scheduler
    • No normalization of the advantage function
    • No entropy bonus (KL term)
    • Remove observation clipping
    • Remove gradient clipping
  3. Combo 3
    • Muon optimizer
    • No gradient normalization
    • No learning rate scheudler
  4. Combo 4
    • Muon optimizer
    • GAE lambda = 1
    • No normalization of advantage function
    • No value function loss clipping
    • No entropy bonus (KL term)
    • No gradient normalization
    • Use shared (backbone) network
    • Smaller learning rate (0.00015)
  5. Combo 5
    • Muon optimizer
    • GAE lambda = 1
    • No normalization of advantage function
    • No value function loss clipping
    • No entropy bonus (KL term)
    • No gradient normalization
    • Use shared (backbone) network
    • Fullbatch
  6. Combo 6
    • Muon optimizer
    • GAE lambda = 1
    • No normalization of advantage function
    • No value function loss clipping
    • No entropy bonus (KL term)
    • No gradient normalization
    • Use shared (backbone) network
    • Fullbatch
    • Tuned learning rate (0.001)
  7. Combo 7
    • Muon optimizer
    • GAE lambda = 0
    • No normalization of advantage function
    • No value function loss clipping
    • No entropy bonus (KL term)
    • No gradient normalization
    • Use shared (backbone) network
    • Fullbatch
    • Tuned learning rate (0.001)
  8. Combo 8
    • Muon optimizer
    • GAE lambda = 1
    • No normalization of advantage function
    • No value function loss clipping
    • No entropy bonus (KL term)
    • No gradient normalization
    • Use shared (backbone) network
    • Fullbatch
    • Tuned learning rate (0.001)
    • Change reward scaling to symlog
    • No LR scheduler

The results for this can be seen here:

(Combo 2 was never run due to issues on the Cluster)

Today's Conclusions

Combo 8 is good enough -- a good tradeoff between removing almost everything, and performance (it's almost the same).

Moving to Other Environments

July 31

This day we decided we should stick to Combo 8 and try it on the other environments. The next environment was chosen to be Ant-v4. Spoiler alert: it didn't work.

We tried checking each ablation one by one, and everything seemed to work individually on Ant. So then we wanted to see what we had to reintroduce in the combo to make the the whole thing work. This resulted in a number of not so interesting runs (and we lost some of them along the way), so we'll only show the highlights. At this point we were going crazy, and started to come up with wild names for the runs. This is reflected in the list:

  • Baseline
    • Just the standard CleanRL implementation
  • Combo 8
    • Muon optimizer
    • GAE lambda = 1
    • No normalization of advantage function
    • No value function loss clipping
    • No entropy bonus (KL term)
    • No gradient normalization
    • Use shared (backbone) network
    • Fullbatch
    • Tuned learning rate (0.001)
    • Change reward scaling to symlog
    • No LR scheduler
  • Just Muon
    • Standard CleanRL implementation
    • Except the optimizer is set to Muon
  • Cocombo Wowombo
    • Same as Combo 8
    • Except the GAE lambda is set to the default value of 0.95

Our conclusion after this set of experiments was that it was the GAE lambda = 1 giving problems. We reset it to 0.95 (default value), but kept all other parameters from Combo 8. We termed this variant Cocombo Wowombo, and it seemed to work.

We then proceeded to run experiments on the environment. In this environment we considered a similar set of groups of hyperparameters:

  • Baseline
    • Just the standard CleanRL implementation
  • Just Muon
    • Standard CleanRL implementation
    • Except the optimizer is set to Muon
  • Cocombo Wowombo
    • Same as Combo 8
    • Except the GAE lambda is set to the default value of 0.95
Wow! This even seems to be outperforming the baseline!

Presentation Day!

August 1

Conclusions:

  • It seems all 37 tricks are kind of necessary to achieve satisfactory performance with PPO. We wasted a bunch of time!
  • If anything, we added a few hyperparameters (Muon optimizer, symlog reward clipping) to make it work better.
